# Spec-Driven Development (SDD)

No plan is drafted without analysis, and no production code without an approved spec.

## States

`pending ‚Üí analyzing ‚Üí needs_clarification ‚Üí spec_ready ‚Üí in_progress ‚Üí done` (or `blocked`).
Only one feature is **active** (`analyzing` or `in_progress`) at a time.

## Flow

0. **Brainstorm (epic, optional)** ‚Äî `/brainstorm <idea>` turns a rough idea into a set of discrete features. The leader proposes a breakdown (slugs, titles, `dependsOn`, order), writes it to `progress/brainstorm_<epic>.md`, and **stops for human approval**. On approval it registers each feature as `pending` via `reins add-feature` (no specs yet) ‚Äî so every feature still earns its own discovery and approval below. This only populates the queue; it never skips a gate.
1. **Discovery (leader)** ‚Äî for a `pending` feature, the leader sets it `analyzing` and investigates the codebase (reads code, launches explorers), then writes `specs/<feature>/discovery.md`: findings, affected areas, approaches, and the **open questions** a human must answer. The feature becomes `needs_clarification` and work **stops**. A bare title is never enough to plan from.
2. **Validate (human)** ‚Äî a human answers the open questions; the leader records them in the discovery's **Resolution**. Use `/validate-discovery <feature>`.
3. **Draft (spec_author)** ‚Äî grounded in the validated discovery, `spec_author` writes:
   - `requirements.md` ‚Äî `R1..Rn` in EARS notation ("WHEN/WHILE/IF ‚Ä¶ the system SHALL ‚Ä¶").
   - `design.md` ‚Äî files to touch, signatures, data shapes, and one rejected alternative.
   - `tasks.md` ‚Äî `T1..Tn` covering every requirement, with a `T ‚Üí R ‚Üí test` table.

   The feature becomes `spec_ready`.
4. **Approve (human)** ‚Äî a human reads the spec and approves; the feature becomes `in_progress`. Use `/approve-spec <feature>`.
5. **Implement** ‚Äî `implementer` builds strictly to the spec, ticking off tasks and writing a test per requirement.
6. **Review** ‚Äî `reviewer` verifies traceability: every `R<n>` has a test, or the change is rejected.

`reins verify` enforces this: a feature in `needs_clarification`, `spec_ready`, or `in_progress` must have a `discovery.md`, only one feature may be active at a time, and `dependsOn` is honored ‚Äî no cycles, no dangling references, and a feature cannot be `in_progress` or `done` until every dependency is `done`.

## Why

Two human gates ‚Äî one on **intent** (discovery) and one on **the plan** (the spec) ‚Äî so misalignment is caught on paper, before a single line of code. Traceability is the difference between "green" and "correct".
